@items.name: baseline
@items.comment:
field_id-instance_id.array_id

field_id determines concept_id
eid+instance_id determines visit_occurrence_id

@items.name: eid
@items.comment: Numerical

@items.name: gp_registrations
@items.comment:
Always registered at GP in your area.
Can be one or more entries for a person, no overlap.
Only available for half of the subjects (not for most of the English population).
Only see when someone moved GP, not to which GP (only data system).

@items.name: data_provider
@items.comment: Data system (Scotland, Wales, Englandx2).

@items.name: reg_date
@items.comment: entry

@items.name: deduct_date
@items.comment: exit date, can be missing, still active GP practices

@items.name: gp_clinical
@items.comment:
Read v2 and Read v3 used by different data providers.
If read code is a lab test, then the value fields contain result. How value1, value2, value3 are used depends on the read code and data_provider.

@items.name: data_provider
@items.comment:
Used for understanding the data
Relevant for ETL, but less for the data itself.

@items.name: event_dt
@items.comment:
Empty event date: 
In source, a placeholder is used (1900-01-01)

@items.name: read_code
@items.comment: Deduced field, read_2 or read_3. Read v2 is subset of Read v3

@items.name: value1
@items.comment:
Some lookups, some corresponding with the one for Caliber. e.g. OPR = operator
Lookups not documented
For now focus on the numeric values.

@items.name: value2
@items.comment: For now focus on the numeric values, ignore the lookups.

@items.name: value3
@items.comment:
Units only captured for one data_provider.
MEAxxx = unit lookup (to be provided)

valueCounts.value: Adcal-D3 chewable tablets tutti frutti (ProStrakan Ltd)

@items.name: hesin
@items.comment:
HES inpatient master table, containing all episodes (admission to certain ward/provider specialty)
All information and metadata on hospitalizations. No outpatient data (only if admitted overnight)
Multiple dates for: admission, episode, discharge. Admission (=spell) longer, episode more granular.
Both admission and episode can have multiple diagnoses.

_uni fields are unified counterparts of regular fields. Provided by UKB

@items.name: ins_index
@items.comment:
Unique key within eid, identifying a visit.
UKB provided field

@items.name: dsource
@items.comment: Data source. Lookups of other fields depend on this.

@items.name: epistart
@items.comment: Within an admission

@items.name: bedyear
@items.comment: Only for data from England, year an episode counts for (administrative)

@items.name: spell_index
@items.comment: If multiple admissions chained together.

@items.name: pctcode
@items.comment: Care site, group of hospitals (primary care trust)

@items.name: category
@items.comment: TBD

@items.name: elecdate
@items.comment: Date decided to be admitted to hospital (administrative, to capture delays)

@items.name: admimeth
@items.comment:
Way a patient was seen (emergency, planned, ...)
Coding depends on dsource

@items.name: person_id
@items.description: A unique identifier for each person.

@items.name: gender_concept_id
@items.description: A foreign key that refers to an identifier in the CONCEPT table for the unique gender of the person.

@items.name: year_of_birth
@items.description: The year of birth of the person. For data sources with date of birth, the year is extracted. For data sources where the year of birth is not available, the approximate year of birth is derived based on any age group categorization available.

@items.name: month_of_birth
@items.description: The month of birth of the person. For data sources that provide the precise date of birth, the month is extracted and stored in this field.

@items.name: gender_source_value
@items.description: The source code for the gender of the person as it appears in the source data. The person’s gender is mapped to a standard gender concept in the Standardized Vocabularies; the original value is stored here for reference.

@items.name: day_of_birth
@items.description: The day of the month of birth of the person. For data sources that provide the precise date of birth, the day is extracted and stored in this field.

@items.name: birth_datetime
@items.description: The date and time of birth of the person.

@items.name: race_concept_id
@items.comment: Is present in UKB data, but >90% 'white british'.
@items.description: A foreign key that refers to an identifier in the CONCEPT table for the unique race of the person.

@items.conceptName: Native Hawaiian or Other Pacific Islander
National surgical quality improvement program defined race unknown

@items.name: race_source_value
@items.description: The source code for the race of the person as it appears in the source data. The person race is mapped to a standard race concept in the Standardized Vocabularies and the original value is stored here for reference.

@items.name: ethnicity_concept_id
@items.comment: NULL
@items.description: A foreign key that refers to the standard concept identifier in the Standardized Vocabularies for the ethnicity of the person.

@items.name: location_id
@items.description: A foreign key to the place of residency for the person in the location table, where the detailed address information is stored.

@items.name: care_site_id
@items.description: A foreign key to the site of primary care in the care_site table, where the details of the care site are stored.

@items.name: provider_id
@items.description: A foreign key to the primary care provider the person is seeing in the provider table.

@items.name: person_source_value
@items.description: An (encrypted) key derived from the person identifier in the source data. This is necessary when a use case requires a link back to the person data at the source dataset.

@items.name: gender_source_concept_id
@items.description: A foreign key to the gender concept that refers to the code used in the source.

@items.name: race_source_concept_id
@items.description: A foreign key to the race concept that refers to the code used in the source.

@items.name: ethnicity_source_value
@items.description: The source code for the ethnicity of the person as it appears in the source data. The person ethnicity is mapped to a standard ethnicity concept in the Standardized Vocabularies and the original code is, stored here for reference.

@items.name: ethnicity_source_concept_id
@items.description: A foreign key to the ethnicity concept that refers to the code used in the source.

@items.name: observation_period
@items.comment: Period different per centre and person.

@items.name: observation_period_id
@items.description: A unique identifier for each observation period.

@items.name: person_id
@items.description: A foreign key identifier to the person for whom the observation period is defined. The demographic details of that person are stored in the person table.

@items.name: observation_period_start_date
@items.description: The start date of the observation period for which data are available from the data source.

@items.name: observation_period_end_date
@items.description: The end date of the observation period for which data are available from the data source.

@items.name: period_type_concept_id
@items.description: A foreign key identifier to the predefined concept in the Standardized Vocabularies reflecting the source of the observation period information
